 <B>A little bit about me...</B>
<P>
<HTML>
I'm working on a Ph.D. in Statistics at the <A
HREF="http://www.stat.umn.edu/"> School of Statistics </A> , <A
HREF="http://www1.umn.edu/tc"> University of Minnesota </A>,
Minneapolis, MN (since September 1997).  I graduated with a B.S. in
Computer Science and minors in Statistics and Film from <A
HREF="http://www.cmu.edu/"> Carnegie Mellon University </A>,
Pittsburgh, PA. (May 1997). I received an M.S. in Statistics from the
University of Minnesota (June 2001). I finished my thesis proposal in
the summer of 2001, so I am now officially a Ph.D. <em>
candidate</em>. <BR><BR>I have been a Research Assistant with <L1> <A
HREF="http://www.stat.umn.edu/~luke"> Luke Tierney </A> since Fall
1999 and have been working with <L1> <A
HREF="http://www.biostat.umn.edu/~brad"> Brad Carlin </A> since Summer
2000. They are jointly advising me on my dissertation (currently
titled <b>Efficient Perfect and MCMC Sampling Methods for Bayesian
Spatial and Components of Variance Models</b>).
<BR>
I am currently working on Bayesian computation for spatial models. In
particular, I am investigating sampling techniques for hierarchical
models that use Gaussian Markov Fields (GMRFs). I am also studying
hierarchical Bayesian modeling techniques used for disease mapping and
particulate matter exposure studies.<BR><BR> The following paper
contains some results from research in MCMC block sampling techniques
for GMRFs.
<P>
<LI> 
<b> Haran, M.</b>, 
<A Href = "http://www.biostat.umn.edu/~hodges">
Hodges, J.S.</A>, and <A Href = "http://www.biostat.umn.edu/~brad">
Carlin, B.P.</A>, ``<A
HREF="ftp://muskie.biostat.umn.edu/pub/2001/rr2001-003.ps.gz">
Accelerating computation in Markov random field models for spatial
data via structured MCMC,</A>'' to appear  <em> Journal of Comp. and
Graph. Statistics </em>, June 2003. 

<! (Research Report 2001-003, Division of Biostatistics, University of Minnesota, 2001).  </li>

<BR><BR> For results from a real world application of Bayesian
modeling (for particulate matter exposure), see
<P>
<LI> <b> Haran, M.</b>, <A Href = "http://www.biostat.umn.edu/~brad"> Carlin, B.P.</A>, Adgate, J.L., Ramachandran, G., <A Href = "http://www.sph.emory.edu/bios/faculty/waller.html"> Waller, L.A.</A>, and <A Href = "http://www.stat.duke.edu/~alan/"> Gelfand, A.E.</A>, 
``<A HREF="http://www.stat.umn.edu/~mharan/hapspgh.ps">
Hierarchical Bayes models for relating particulate matter exposure
measures,</A>, Case Studies in Bayesian Statistics, Volume VI, 
eds. C.Gatsonis, et al., New York:  Springer-Verlag, 2002.
<BR><BR> I am currently working on perfect sampling approaches for Bayesian disease mapping models. For more information on perfect sampling, see <A Href = "http://dbwilson.com/exact/"> D.B.Wilson's website </A>.
Among the research interests I would like to pursue in the future (in addition to statistical computing and hierarchical models) are: spatial modeling, prior elicitation and measurement error modeling. 

